<br>
 This is Jeff Wright from Pinson Alabama.  Perhaps you are aware of my recent column:<br>
<br>
www.spacedaily.com/news/oped-03z.html<br>
<br>
     I am sure that you have received all kinds of crank concepts, but none of them have the benefit of having been flight proven as my &quot;American Energia-Buran-type&quot; shuttle replacement has been. Many have tried to downplay Energia-Buran's success but have nothing to offer in its place: This was true of an Air &amp; Space article I debunked.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE AUTOLINK START--><a href="http://groups.yahoo.com/group/HumanSpaceflight/message/370">groups.yahoo.com/group/Hu...essage/370</a><!--EZCODE AUTOLINK END--><br>
<br>
<br>
     Much has been written about our current Shuttle, how the Air Force inflated its design and how Nixon sold the original down the river, etc.<br>
<br>
     But all this talk is of no importance whatsoever, seeing as the laws of physics bend to no man.<br>
<br>
     Two-Stage-To-Orbit (TSTO) designs give us two sets of wings, landing gear, heat-shield, etc. and are very heavy. It simply could not have been done in the 1970s and is not likely possible today. This is also true of Single-Stage-To-Orbit designs which are more than cryogenic eggshells/hypersonic dirigibles. The X-33 was proof of this, seeing that having the entirety of a launcher shielded makes for weight creep that leaves you with no payload of any kind. And this is assuming the X-33's questionable composite tanks worked where they quite obviously failed. (&quot;But we learned so much...&quot;) DC-X at least used 2219 alloy aluminum.<br>
<br>
     Small spaceplanes are even worse, and weight creep is even more of a factor, as I have described.<br>
<br>
     The only thing for it is to ignore the pundits who insist that we never mix crew and cargo--when that in fact is structurally the BEST thing to do, seeing that a Buran-sized space-shuttle is scaled up big enough for weight-creep to be less of an issue (allowing for off the shelf components, looser tolerences, etc.)--yet iscompact enough to be built with current materials since the bulk of cryogenic propellants and engine-mass remain outside the orbiters dense, safe airframe that is of simple build.<br>
<br>
     Many go on-and-on about how the shuttle is 1970s technology. But this just goes to prove my point. The Columbia was 1970s technology--meaning it had a mundane, center-of-envelope design and was very much overbuilt.<br>
<br>
     And it still failed. <br>
<br>
     This leads me to believe that it was not in fact conservative enough--which should give us pause, and does give us less reasons to risk lives on unproven designs. That does not mean we cannot use the latest in proven materials, avionics, heat-shields, and the like.<br>
<br>
     But leave the basic shape alone. The shuttle looks the way it does for a reason. The engines are all on ground level for ease of inspection, and the External Tank, unencumbered by wings, landing-gear, etc. is simpler than any winged first stage.<br>
<br>
     Remember, not only do people have to ride on these craft, but someone has to build them too. And service them.<br>
<br>
     What many purists do not understand is that re-usability and serviceability can be, and frequently are, two different things.<br>
<br>
     Let me give you two examples. You may remember the German high-speed rail accident where railway cars smashed against a bridge. This happened due to cracks in the 'tires' that lined the wheels. The Germans did not X-ray the wheels as often as they needed do---as is often done with the front steering tires of tractor-trailer rigs here. In a similar incident a rollercoaster car of German manufacture failed due to the inability to service crucial parts. Remind me to tell you why whoever invented pop-rivets should be locked up--but that's another story.<br>
<br>
     The current space shuttle may not be all that usable. But that is not the point at all. In the current safety-first mindset NASA is, or should be in, what with limited flight rates that are likely to remain limited--total re-usability is not needed, nor should be desired.<br>
<br>
     The problem with our shuttle is that it is not easlily serviceable. Chris Kraft's impatience notwithstanding, it is the Ron Dittemore school of thought in being a &quot;wise steward&quot; which must prevail.<br>
<br>
     Buran was a far superior concept to Columbia, even if Russian quality controls and materials left much to be desired in that the orbiter and main propulsion hydrogen engines were kept separate. With the 'airplane people' and the 'rocket people' kept away from each other--with a strong Chief Designer making sure that all the kingpins and holes line up--the work on Buran continued apace.<br>
<br>
     Buran landed after two automated orbits with no tiles missing due to the foresight and maturity of the Chief Designer who understood the need for a modular launch vehicle that could serve the Soviet Union, which collapsed due to several generations of ICBMs, the $20 billion dollar BAM railway, foreign entanglements, and military waste. as I have explained in my letter to Air &amp; SPACE (see above).<br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
     The foresight of Glushko and the modular design of Energia's kerosene strap-ons allowed them to outlive turmoil to become the basis of the Sea Launch vehicle Zenit, which uses the RD-170 engine that the Atlas V EELV motor (RD-180) is based on. <br>
<br>
     This was not true of the Saturn V which was, indeed, too much of what it was--that being a goal-oriented vehicle made first and foremost to land men on the moon. If you remember the proposed LUNEX mission concepts, you will see that more4 modular vehicles were proposed. The increase of non-goal oriented capabilities is what is needed now. The Soviet Chief Designers, making launchers much larger than what their military really wanted or needed--used the large primitive designs of early Soviet nukes as an excuse to build a space booster. This gave the Russians a head start, allowing the R-7 and Proton to gain a foothold as the launch market developed. Sadly, the comsat-people wish to stifle innovation, forgetting that the reason the EELV market fell was due to the leadership of launch vehicle designers of years before who glutted the market--making it their own.<br>
I prove this in the piece below:<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE AUTOLINK START--><a href="http://groups.yahoo.com/group/inside_ksc/message/6932">groups.yahoo.com/group/in...ssage/6932</a><!--EZCODE AUTOLINK END--> <br>
<br>
     On to other matters...<br>
<br>
      The OSP, be it capsule or lifting-body, must be cancelled. It can have no payload bay from which to do work or apply controlled force. The astronaut can thereby have no purchase. Buran style orbiters, and yes even Columbia-style orbiters, are stable, and having a virtual 'floor' give greater psychological stability. I have seen laughable artist conceptions depicting a lone astronaut trying to work on Hubble all but dangling out away from the OSP trying to retrieve bits (drawn undersize) from a small compartment from the expendable trans-stage flying behind the OSP--which would be lost in an abort should the Delta IV fail. Since each CCB of a Delta IV heavy has only one engine--it has no engine-out capability like what was found on Energia with several engines feeding from one common tank--allowing one engine to fail while still allowing the mission to succeed.<br>
<br>
 My engine-equipped External Tank with simple orbiter would fly with less stress upon its airframe:<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE AUTOLINK START--><a href="http://groups.yahoo.com/group/inside_ksc/message/6903">groups.yahoo.com/group/in...ssage/6903</a><!--EZCODE AUTOLINK END--><br>
<br>
<br>
     An OSP would need a three-CCB Delta IV heavy and the transtage is still thrown away, unlike the Burans tail which is a restartable trans-stage retro-package that is part of the returning orbiter. Trans-stages can be quite expensive. Small systems--and OSPs-- can cost as much as larger systems (Osprey vs. A-380). The fans of OSP want to launch a limited number of small systems, where we in fact should make sure that we should have the same number of launches carry much harger payloads to decrease price-per-pound.<br>
<br>
     A three-RS-68-equipped External Tank using SRBs (for now) will be able to take 100 ton payload pods or simpler 80 ton Buran-type orbiters with 20 tons of large interior stores. The rear of each orbiter will have kerosene/LOX tanks with orbital insertion engines in the very back. Both of these systems in my design would be able to slide back and out on a fork-lift-type device (the maneuver engine-cassette more often than the tankage behind it) for ease of turnaround. New engines go up as the older engines are re-furbished on stands. <br>
<br>
     The External Tanks have RS-68s that will be close to the orbiter when mounted, which mean that with the tank lying prone, the engines should be near hip level when the External Tank is checked out while lying down using the horizontal integration we learned from the Russians.<br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
     Our STS became demonized since you had to launch 90 ton orbiters just for the 20 tons of cargo they had inside--no better than the (more expensive) Titan IV. People then began to hate these larger orbiters forgetting that the laws of physics only allow that type of winged craft to be buildable with SSTOs being whales and mini-spaceplanes being mice.<br>
<br>
     Energia/Buran never had a chance to prove itself, so it became a scapegoat. If the United States had flown it over 100 times, with many of the launches being unmanned payload pods that could lift off without the weather being perfect the world over--ISS would have been finished years ago and our human presence in space would be 20 years ahead of where it is now. With engines under the External Tank, you are not limited to just one kind of orbiter since it no longer has the cryogenic main engines. This allows you to launch a heavy metal heatshielded passenger orbiter, a Buran-type cargo/service orbiter with tile very like Buran but with an F-111 type escape cockpit/capsule, hypersonic test craft, 100 ton cargos or outsized aerobrake disks, etc.<br>
<br>
     When a true spaceplane can be developed, my engine-equipped External Tank can be ringed with strap-ons to become a Mars-ship launcher. True Heavy Lift needs to come first, not last to give us a stable foundation for the future. I explain this below:<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE AUTOLINK START--><a href="http://groups.yahoo.com/group/inside_ksc/message/6947">groups.yahoo.com/group/in...ssage/6947</a><!--EZCODE AUTOLINK END--><br>
<br>
<br>
     Full sized orbiters with greater tolerances can be swapped out with large cargo pods, allowing speedier construction. The recovery of SSMEs on Orbiters with their costly refurbishments have forced us to construct ISS with a large number of launchers--costing us more money than they could save. SSMEs are more trouble than they are worth, and the engines most likely to be flown back will be coke-filled kerosene motors needed for thrust on lift off.<br>
<br>
     Shuttle-C concepts are maxed out as soon as they are built, will be of limited run, disallowing amortization of costs, and cannot evolve into larger vehicles as can en engine equipped External Tank. I fear that if we go to capsules, the 39 series pads will rust away and never be used again.<br>
<br>
     Let us not turn away from true Heavy-Lift, since that was what lifted the nations interest in the days of Apollo.<br>
<br>
     Or will we follow the defunct &quot;faster, better, cheaper...&quot; mantra with:<br>
<br>
<br>
                                Abandon In Place.<br>
